summary: This is an email exchange between legal or investigative personnel discussing coordination with Ghislaine Maxwell's attorneys regarding a draft letter, and an investigative lead concerning Larry Visoski and a potential connection to a Customs and Border Protection (CBP) officer. The sender expresses skepticism about the significance of the Visoski lead.

connections.description: The email discusses investigating a potential connection between Visoski and Epstein, but the author states Visoski didn't think he was friends with Epstein.
Visoski had the CBP officer's phone number in his phone, but according to the proffer, he didn't remember the officer.

events.title: Email coordination on Maxwell case
events.description: Legal/investigative team discusses conferring with Maxwell's attorneys and preparing a draft letter due by 5:00 PM.

events.title: Proffer from Larry Visoski's counsel
events.description: Counsel for Larry Visoski provided a proffer regarding a potential connection to a CBP officer, which was initially described as promising but later viewed skeptically.

keyFacts: The document is an email from July 28, 2020, showing active legal/investigative work related to the Ghislaine Maxwell case.
A proffer was received from Larry Visoski's attorney concerning a potential connection between Visoski and a Customs and Border Protection (CBP) officer.
The email author is skeptical of the Visoski lead, stating Visoski had the CBP officer's number but didn't remember him and didn't know of a significant or nefarious connection to Jeffrey Epstein.
The team planned to have agents join an interview with Visoski but did not consider the lead promising at that stage.
The email discusses the need to send a draft letter to Maxwell's attorneys by 5:00 PM on that date.
